[5] Suspected, research, drugs, vaccines, funding

14 Jun 2015 Guinea: Ebola - a test too far for one little girl
http://www.who.int/features/2015/guinea-ebola-resources/en/
[In Guinea, the Ebola outbreak continues and resources are needed to end the epidemic. When testing and treatment options are too far away, people are less willing to cooperate]
[This article, about a young girl whose family is reluctant to send her 3 hrs away for Ebola testing, raises the ongoing problems of lack of resources readily accessible to the communities. - Mod.LK]

13 Jun 2015 Guinea, Guinea-Bissau: (UN`s) International Organization for Migration (IOM) & CDC conduct Ebola assessment in Boke
http://www.newshour.com.bd/2015/06/13/iom-and-cdc-conduct-ebola-virus-disease-outbreak-assessment-in-boke-guinea
[In mid-May [2015], a new Ebola Virus Disease (EVD) outbreak was declared in Boke Prefecture... "Recent development of the epidemic in the Prefecture of Boke at the border with Guinea-Bissau increases the risk of introduction of Ebola into this unaffected country," said Alexandre Robert, Ebola Regional Project Officer. The assessment team found monitoring of population mobility and cross-border movements for EVD infected travellers and contact cases will be a great challenge.]

11 Jun 2015 Liberia: no teacher, no school -- after Ebola, instructors skip over pay
http://allafrica.com/stories/201506111823.html?viewall=1
[In many schools, teachers are abandoning the classrooms, interrupting learning activities in many schools. To add to this unfortunate situation, students are protesting against lack of teachers in the schools, blocking traffic and hurting business.]
[This is another aspect of the fallout of the Ebola outbreak that must be considered in assessing overall damage. - Mod.LK]

12 Jun 2015 Liberia: 'Don't travel to Sierra Leone, Guinea'
http://allafrica.com/stories/201506121706.html
[Because of the continuing Ebola outbreak in Guinea and Sierra Leone, Liberia has issued a travel and health alert recommending Liberians avoid traveling to those 2 countries]

12 Jun 2015 Nigeria: Civil rights group urges President Buhari to investigate health ministry for mistreatment of Ebola volunteers
http://saharareporters.com/2015/06/12/civil-rights-group-urges-president-buhari-investigate-health-ministry-mistreatment-ebola
[Access to Justice, a Nigerian civil rights organization, has requested the African Union and the Nigerian government to investigate the many allegations of maltreatment of Nigerian Ebola mission volunteers. According to the news source Premium Times, these allegations include the Nigerian Ministry of Health's failure to adequately organize and execute the volunteers operations, and volunteers being short-changed on salaries, food, and accommodations. They also faced sexual harassment and deportation]

12 Jun 2015: Sierra Leone imposes new Ebola curfew
http://www.iol.co.za/news/africa/sierra-leone-imposes-new-ebola-curfew-1.1871189#.VXsqq1LLLnk
[Due to the steady increase in new Ebola cases, on Fri [12 Jun 2015], President Koroma declared a 21-day curfew (with other restrictions), with immediate effect, for Ebola hot spots in an attempt to keep people from leaving parts of Kambia and Port Loko districts. The chiefdom-level curfew will restrict movements from 6 pm to 6 am. Those who violate the curfew will be detained and prosecuted. Night patrols will be used in an attempt to stop people escaping by vehicles. Authorities believe running away on foot will only get them so far [a short way] before they are apprehended. According to authorities, Ebola continues to spread in these 2 districts due to people leaving quarantined homes and exposing others to the disease. More than 12 contacts have escaped curfew. In addition, Sierra Leone's parliament is extending the state of public health emergency for another 90 days. There have also been breaches of anti-Ebola regulations in the capital. A member of parliament, Alie Badara Munu, was arrested for participating in a traditional [i.e. unsafe] burial in May 2015]

12 Jun 2015 Sierra Leone, Guinea: Ebola cases in Sierra Leone spike to highest level since March [2015]
http://www.cbc.ca/news/health/ebola-cases-in-sierra-leone-spike-to-highest-level-since-march-1.3111509
[Sierra Leone and Guinea are still regularly reporting several new cases daily. As a result, both countries' leadership extended emergency measures. According to the National Ebola Response Centre (NERC) of Sierra Leone, because of noncompliance with anti-Ebola measures, more than a dozen people escaped from quarantine in May 2015. The NERC indicates that, on 9 Jun 2015, Sierra Leone reported 7 new confirmed cases, the highest number since 9 Mar 2015]

11 Jun 2015 (USA): Mass media and the contagion of fear: the case of Ebola in America
http://journals.plos.org/plosone/article?id=10.1371/journal.pone.0129179

12 Jun 2015 USA (CT): Report: Milford paid USD30 000 to settle Ebola lawsuit
http://wtnh.com/2015/06/13/report-milford-paid-30k-to-settle-ebola-lawsuit/
[A newly released document shows the insurance carrier for the city of Milford [Connecticut] paid USD 30 000 to settle a lawsuit filed by the family of a 3rd-grader who was barred from school for several days because of Ebola fears. School officials initially told the 7-year-old [child] to stay out of school for 3 weeks last October [2014] after she attended a family wedding in Nigeria. See original report at
http://wtnh.com/2014/10/29/milford-parents-speak-about-keeping-student-from-school-over-ebola-concerns.]

[Nigeria is a country that hadn't seen an Ebola case in nearly 2 months and is hundreds of miles from the epicenter of the Ebola outbreak. The little girl was not sick, not in quarantine, and was getting a Milford Schools tutor sent to her home. This shows lack of education about Ebola on the part of some parents and the school board, which acted out of an abundance of caution, as the saying goes. - Mod.JW]

